t Not Unusual: Violence in Canadian Families is the first book to offer a national survey of the latest research and practice, and it reflects on the patriarchal roots and societal conditions in Canada that have led to the long-standing abuse of women and children. While feminist theories provide an overarching framework, a broad range of approaches is offered to examine and respond to critical aspects of this serious social problem. Topics include: systemic oppression of Aboriginal families and communities; violence in a francophone minority context; child corporal punishment; abuse in the lives of people with disabilities; the objectification of older adults; mother blaming; intimate violence in same-sex relationships; and new approaches to solving the problem of violence in Canadian families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbused older peoplezCanada. 0aChildren and violencezCanada. 0aFamily violencezCanada. 0aWomenxViolence againstzCanada. 4aFamily & Relationships: Child Abuse. 4aFamily & Relationships: Domestic Violence. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh1 aAlaggia, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlaggia, Ramona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAvis, Judith Myers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaskin, Cyndy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirnbaum, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, April, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDergal, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Shaindl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v